46","1200–1246":"1200–1246","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1225–1292":"1225–1292","1238–1302":"1238–1302","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1242–Male":"1242–Deceased","1181–1246":"1181–1246","1184–1229":"1184–1229","1242":"1242","1240":"1240","1184":"1184","1292":"1292","1181":"1181","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1302":"1302","after 1229":"after 1229","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1200":"1200","about 1238":"about 1238","1210":"1210","about 1246":"about 1246","about 1202":"about 1202","about 1200":"about 1200","about 1240":"about 1240","after 1246":"after 1246","1229":"1229","Tunstall, Lancashire, England":"Tunstall, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Cantsfield, Lancashire, England":"Cantsfield, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tunstall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>tūn-stall</i> ‘site of a farm, farmstead’, notably Tunstall (Lancashire) and one or more of many Staffordshire places (Tunstall near Stoke on Trent, Tunstall near Adbaston, and four places called Dunstall), but also Tunstall Farm in Mountfield (Sussex) and possibly also Tunstall (Durham, Kent, Norfolk, Shropshire, Suffolk, east and North Yorkshire), and Dunstall (Lincolnshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tunstill","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Tunstall  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Tunstall II was born about 1200, in Tunstall, Lancashire, England, his father, Thomas de Tunstall, was 21 and his mother, Maud de Austwick, was 18. He had at least 4 sons with Eda Cantsfield. He died after 1246, in Lancashire, England."},"et":{"about 1200–after 1246":"umbes 1200–pärast 1246","1200–1246":"1200–1246","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1225–1292":"1225–1292","1238–1302":"1238–1302","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1181–1246":"1181–1246","1184–1229":"1184–1229","1242":"1242","1240":"1240","1184":"1184","1292":"1292","1181":"1181","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1302":"1302","after 1229":"pärast 1229","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1200":"1200","about 1238":"umbes 1238","1210":"1210","about 1246":"umbes 1246","about 1202":"umbes 1202","about 1200":"umbes 1200","about 1240":"umbes 1240","after 1246":"pärast 1246","1229":"1229","Tunst